column18:
While many scholars have established the need for an integration of information literacy within the metaliteracy framework (Hung, 2010; Mackey & Jacobson, 2001; Mahiri, 2011), many librarians often struggle with implementing digital literacy within the information literacy education (Becker, 2018). This presentation offers a discussion about integration of the digital literacy curriculum in the first-year mandatory credit-bearing information literacy course delivered online in collaboration with the Critical Analysis, Reading and Writing Academic Works course. Using iterative design principles, the presenter will discuss learning objectives, delivery and assessment methods for cultivating responsible digital citizens and building a community of learning online. Through the alternative assessment methods, such as evidence journal, as well as reflective practice, this project-based course demonstrates the application of the best practices in instructional design to implement critical digital curriculum in information literacy education. The learning outcomes for this session are as follows:

a) The attendees will learn about the process of designing critical digital literacy curriculum with the special emphasis on critical information literacy practices;

b) The best practices in instructional design as applied to the information literacy course design will be discussed and demonstrated;

c) The session attendees will leave with a set of recommendations on how to encourage students to become critical consumers of information in the age of algorithms, considering their digital footprints.

