column18:
The summer of 2020 saw two key cultural and social moments that will continue to shift the way people look at digital library materials. COVID-19 and Black Lives Matter will fundamentally change the way libraries and patrons interact with collections. COVID-19 saw an increase in internet usage. Including massive amounts of professionals working from home as well as the closure of physical library spaces, institutions continue to work on bringing more material online in order to showcase collections and keep the public informed. With the Black Lives Matter movement in 2020 there is a new, important emphasis on showcasing Black, Indigenous, and People of Color (BIPOC) communities works among libraries.

Taking these two considerations together we should look at how technology can play a part in helping to showcase BIPOC in an age with an increase in expectations of online access. Linked Open Data is an internet technology that promises to connect internet resources via the semantic web. This could have profound implications for the sharing of important documents and other materials by or about BIPOC.

This panel will discuss how the University of South Florida Libraries linked data team is working to use linked data to promote our cultural heritage collections. The panel members include librarians from digital scholarship, library resources management, and digital collections. The panel discussion will cover the benefits of Linked Open Data, building connections between resources across platforms, and bridging library users and the collections together. The panel will highlight how linked data technology:

1. provides better access and discoverability to cultural heritage collections;

2. allows important cultural heritage collections to be more easily sharable and reusable for various educational and research purposes;

3. increases the access and interoperability of cultural heritage collections to promote greater impact and awareness of different cultures to serve underrepresented populations.

